NIS is a decent all-in-one package (AV, firewall, parental controls, antispam) that makes everything pretty easy. This constitutes the majority of its appeal. It’s also moderately configurable but lacking some key options and is notoriously bad about not allowing programs full net access even when you’ve set it to “Permit all” (see WinGAIM faq).
This computer is actually using it right now (my brother’s, parents had to set it up so NIS all the way). The antivirus is bad about flagging tools I use every day (why does it have a “Hacktool” category on autodelete?) and also doesn’t catch a lot of packed/bonded malware variants.
If you’re just using the antivirus you pretty much are wasting money, much better options for the same or less money exist.

On my computer I’m using NOD (good) and BlackICE (decent).
